{"id":"project-LICHEN-k8zm","title":"Inconsistent error handling pattern in Trickle non-try methods","description":"File: rust/lichen-rpl/src/trickle.rs
Lines: 136-138, 149-151, 171-172

The Trickle module has both try_ and non-try versions of methods with inconsistent error handling:

```rust
// fire_transmit returns bool, swallowing any error
pub fn fire_transmit(&mut self) -> bool {
    self.try_fire_transmit().unwrap_or(false)
}

// expire ignores the error entirely
pub fn expire(&mut self, now: u32, rand_offset: u32) {
    let _ = self.try_expire(now, rand_offset);
}

// reset also ignores errors
pub fn reset(&mut self, now: u32, rand_offset: u32) {
    let _ = self.try_reset(now, rand_offset);
}
```

Impact:
1. fire_transmit returns false on error, which is the same as 'suppressed' - caller can't distinguish
2. expire and reset silently do nothing on error
3. State machine violations go undetected
4. Debugging becomes difficult when timer behaves unexpectedly

This is a design pattern issue rather than a functional bug, but it could mask bugs in callers.

Recommendation: Either:
1. Remove non-try versions and require explicit error handling
2. Add debug_assert! or log/defmt in non-try versions
3. Document clearly that errors are swallowed and when they can occur","status":"open","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:41:31.149857Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:41:31.149892Z"}

